              <span id="reviewTextContainer21688474" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15368095478419799048">This is the sequel to Sister of My Heart, which I enjoyed. But I couldn&apos;t get through this one -- I confess I didn&apos;t try very hard. It just is too much in the heads of all the characters -- too psychoanalytical for my tastes. Too much angst, too much insecurity, too much &quot;what do I do and who am I,&quot; too much reflection and not enough action. Although I wanted to see what happened to the characters that I liked in the first book, the answer ended up to be &quot;not much&quot; -- one woman&apos;s husband falls i</span>
  <span id="freeText15368095478419799048" style="display:none">This is the sequel to Sister of My Heart, which I enjoyed. But I couldn't get through this one -- I confess I didn't try very hard. It just is too much in the heads of all the characters -- too psychoanalytical for my tastes. Too much angst, too much insecurity, too much "what do I do and who am I," too much reflection and not enough action. Although I wanted to see what happened to the characters that I liked in the first book, the answer ended up to be "not much" -- one woman's husband falls in love with her best friend who has come to live with her, and they all need to deal with the fall-out. Yup, got it in the first 20 pages. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15368095478419799048" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
