        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1263396466" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11373218431105348173">After enjoying Sister of My Heart so much and putting it down as one of my favorite books ever, the sequel to it came down to nothing but a disappointment. Perhaps it’s all due to the fact that I took too long before I read it and I’m no longer a young 21 year old girl, but rather a more serious mid-20s reader. I felt that Sudha did not have to betray Anju like that(to me it was a major betrayal, a dealbreaker!), despite everything she felt:isn’t that what ‘sisters of the heart’ are supposed to </span>
  <span id="freeText11373218431105348173" style="display:none">After enjoying Sister of My Heart so much and putting it down as one of my favorite books ever, the sequel to it came down to nothing but a disappointment. Perhaps it’s all due to the fact that I took too long before I read it and I’m no longer a young 21 year old girl, but rather a more serious mid-20s reader. I felt that Sudha did not have to betray Anju like that(to me it was a major betrayal, a dealbreaker!), despite everything she felt:isn’t that what ‘sisters of the heart’ are supposed to do? Furthermore, most of the characters just seem unsure of themselves, their feelings are scattered all over and I really felt that it was unfair, given how strong they had been in the first book.<br /><br />Nevertheless, it’s still better than your average book although I recommend that you read it soon after reading Sister of My Heart. <br /><br /></span>
