<div id="review_556498920" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/556498920" />
    <a title="Simran" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13293003-simran"><img alt="Simran" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1563470846p2/13293003.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/556498920?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Simran" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Simran" href="/user/show/13293003-simran">Simran</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13293003-simran?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer556498920" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8171183639640522076">She leaves me speechless! She never fails to leave the reader craving for more. She never disappoints!<br/>Chitra Banerjee Divakaruni is one of the finest Indian authors of our times. Her writing style, the way she unfolds the story, the depth of her characters, the words and imagery she uses, everything is commendable!<br/>This book, The Vine of Desire, I stumbled upon it by chance in the library. I did not know that it was a continuation to the &apos;&apos;Sister of my Heart&apos;&apos;, which I&apos;d read a few months ago. I </span>
  <span id="freeText8171183639640522076" style="display:none">She leaves me speechless! She never fails to leave the reader craving for more. She never disappoints!<br />Chitra Banerjee Divakaruni is one of the finest Indian authors of our times. Her writing style, the way she unfolds the story, the depth of her characters, the words and imagery she uses, everything is commendable!<br />This book, The Vine of Desire, I stumbled upon it by chance in the library. I did not know that it was a continuation to the ''Sister of my Heart'', which I'd read a few months ago. I was delighted when I read the names Sudha and Anju on the back cover. The very same women about whom I've been craving to read more, as I turned to the last page of ''Sister of my Heart''. Finally, I'd gotten a chance!<br /><br />The Vine of Desire - ''Asha-lata, the mythical desire vine which gives you whatever you wish for. It gives you what you want, but it always turn out different from what you imagined it to be''.<br />The theme of the book is enticing. I think almost every reader could relate with one character or the other. Mostly, Sudha. The desire, the dreams and hopes in life that one cannot escape. And what terrible conditions it leaves us into! <br />The journey from childhood to womanhood. The unfulfilled dreams, the dreams that came true but not in the true sense. The situations that twisted, the loneliness that became a part of their everyday lives. The seeds of hatred that the fate planted. But in spite of everything that happened, the love that the two women shared, could not be turned into hatred. It's true. Sometimes we love someone so deeply, that even the most terrible blows of fate cannot destroy it. As Pishi rightly said, ''Can the left hand ever hate the right?''.<br /><br />I wonder if these women actually live in some corner of the world. Or maybe they lived on Earth a long time ago and now ''they are like droplets of seawater and ash, riding the air?''. <br />Once again, the author has left me craving for more. Once again, it's like losing a best friend, as you turn to the last page of a book. How I wish it never had to come to an end!<br /><br />But, the messages that I've grasped from this book, will always stay in my heart. And my favorite phrases, I'm going to write them down, to read again and again. And to get inspired, again and again!<br /><br />May we have more writers like her in our country!</span>
  <a data-text-id="8171183639640522076" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


