  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1729965404" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1729965404" />
    <a title="Emily" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13417219-emily"><img alt="Emily" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1621014711p2/13417219.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1729965404?book_show_action=true">Sep 10, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Emily" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Emily" href="/user/show/13417219-emily">Emily</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1729965404" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9183693069937266047">This is a tough review to write. I loved, loved, loved the first book in this series and couldn&apos;t wait to read the sequel. But as I started reading this, I found myself wondering if it was even written by the same author or why she had changed so much between the two books. The style of this one was quite different, more poetic and less straightforward, using lots of metaphors and sentence fragments. Although there was still some stirring, evocative prose that I loved, there were several non-tra</span>
  <span id="freeText9183693069937266047" style="display:none">This is a tough review to write. I loved, loved, loved the first book in this series and couldn't wait to read the sequel. But as I started reading this, I found myself wondering if it was even written by the same author or why she had changed so much between the two books. The style of this one was quite different, more poetic and less straightforward, using lots of metaphors and sentence fragments. Although there was still some stirring, evocative prose that I loved, there were several non-traditional techniques used in this book that weren't present in the first, and I found that unexpected and jarring. <br /><br />For example: the inclusion of many letters (which I didn't mind, except the crossed out ones; that was just strange) and the telling of the story from so many different POVs. I really didn't care for the inclusion of anyone's POV other than Anju and Sudha's, and especially not the baby, Dayita's -- yuck). There were also several sections that included gimmicks like "What I said", "What I thought but didn't say", etc., which I also didn't like. Some parts of the book were in the same style as the first book, but then the author would go off on flights of fancy, as if she were trying out different techniques she learned in creative writing class. I also didn't really enjoy the fact that the setting of the majority of this book was in the US rather than in India, and the mothers were basically left behind and only rarely given voice. It just all seemed too modern vs. the first book, which was so much more interesting in its portrayal of Indian culture.<br /><br />I guess what it possibly boils down to is that this book just felt much more contemporary than the first, and that would have been fine if it was a standalone novel; but as a sequel, it was just not quite my cup of "cha". :-)</span>
  <a data-text-id="9183693069937266047" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

